      <h3 class="Work_heading">Cloud Collectors</h3>
      <p>A young adult fantasy inspired by the Inuit culture of Greenland and the Danish invasions in the 1800s. I’ve spent some time in Greenland, Iceland and Denmark and I couldn’t pick between the three of them for my favourite place to live.</p>
      <p>It’s Stardust meets Howl’s Moving Castle meets Casablanca!</p>
      <p>Early chapters of this work have been workshopped as part of my master’s degree with Australian author Penni Russon in the subject Young Adult fiction, and later on with Lili Wilkinson at Writers Victoria.</p>
      <p>I’ve had fun with this story, playing around with what it means to be a hero and have power. Neither Anuk or Elena spend a lot of time acting like heroes, even when they think they do. But then adversity reveals character doesn’t it. While there’s airships and some tech the focus for me has always been these two characters that have been in my head for the past seven years. It’s also really important to me that there is a diverse cast in my stories as well. It represents the world we live in.</p>
      <p>Cute story, but if I never wrote this book, I wouldn’t have met my fiancé. About five years ago, when I first starting writing CC, I had an idea for a charming villain called Aksel, who was tall and thin, with impressive cheekbones.</p>
      <p>One day I was leading a bunch of the new exchange students on the university campus tour, when I noticed one particularly attractive man with stunning bone structure, and I thought, ‘he looks just like my character.’ The attractive student introduced himself in his French accent, ‘Erh hello, my name is Axel,’ and I stood there holding his hand for a long awkward amount of time.</p>
      <p>He’s tried to convince me to make Aksel the hero, but sorry my love, no such luck.</p>
